<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUEZ CANAL TO LOSE 10% OF REVENUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CAIRO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Suez Canal, one of Egypt's main sources of badly needed hard currency, is 
expected to lose 10% of its revenues this year as a result of the U.N. blockade 
of Iraq, an official said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Izzat Adel, chairman of the Suez Canal authority, told the state-owned 
Middle East News Agency that before the embargo was imposed in August, Iraq and 
Kuwait accounted for the annual export of 7 million tons of oil through the 
canal. 
</P>
<P>
Their imports through the international waterway were also halted as a result 
of the embargo, imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait on Aug. 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
