<HEADLINE>
<P>
BEER SALE BAN AT UCLA GAMES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This fan got more exercised than the Bruin football team at the Rose Bowl on 
Sept. 8. Certain actions, supposedly taken out of consideration for public 
safety, apparently had more to do with making up for the loss of beer sale 
profits to UCLA and the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
As in past years, I had a "sipper cup" in my hand as I entered the gate. The 
gate staff told me containers were forbidden. I pointed out that the cup was 
empty, the temperature was 100 degrees and I wanted to drink water. 
</P>
<P>
"Oh, we'll sell you a bottle of water," they said, "but you'll have to check 
your container at the gate and pick it up after the game." Boy am I stupid! I 
cooperated. I anticipated a wait at the claim check booth and left the game 
early. After standing in line for 30 minutes, I handed in my claim check and 
was told by the girl, "Oh yeah, I remember seeing one like that, but it's not 
here now." 
</P>
<P>
I've promised myself that I will not spend one nickel at the concessions stands 
this year. Next year, they'll probably ban bringing food into the stadium, but 
that's OK because I don't plan on renewing my season tickets. 
</P>
<P>
Despite all the sanctimonious talk about encouraging a "family" atmosphere at 
the Rose Bowl, the real driver here was the profit motive. 
</P>
<P>
Alums can still get loaded on beer for a buck at the private party in the 
parking lot and hypocrisy, not football, is the name of the game. 
</P>
<P>
ELLEN FROST 
</P>
<P>
Woodland Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
