<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ANAHEIM; 
</P>
<P>
TREE ORDINANCE UP FOR VOTE TUESDAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LISA MASCARO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council Tuesday will consider a new street tree ordinance that would 
make it clear that the city -- and not its residents -- owns the trees on 
parkways. 
</P>
<P>
The ordinance has been years in the making but received new attention when the 
city chopped down about three dozen 70-year-old oak and ash trees on the north 
side of Broadway a few months ago. 
</P>
<P>
Residents who had lived there for decades were upset and formed a group that 
managed to save the trees on the south side of the street. 
</P>
<P>
Currently, residents may plant or remove trees with city permission. The new 
ordinance would leave that to the city. 
</P>
<P>
The proposal allows residents to appeal decisions to the department director, 
who may consult an outside arborist. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier, residents had recommended that the appeals be made instead through a 
residents committee, a proposition the council may consider. LISA MASCARO 
</P>
</TEXT>
