<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAND REFORM VOTE URGED BY GORBACHEV 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, assailed for indecision on overhauling the 
economy, called today for a national referendum on whether to end the 
collectivization of farmland and return it to individuals. 
</P>
<P>
It apparently would be the first national referendum ever in the Soviet Union, 
and Gorbachev's proposal reflects the deep split in opinion about how to rescue 
the economy. 
</P>
<P>
He spoke a day after 50,000 protesters marched to the Kremlin and demanded the 
resignation of Gorbachev and his prime minister over the state of the economy, 
which is plagued by under-productivity and worsening consumer shortages. 
</P>
<P>
In a 30-minute address to the national Parliament today, Gorbachev said the 
fate of farmland "is too big a decision, comrades, to be made in offices, 
auditoriums or meeting halls -- even as important as the one in which we are 
working today." 
</P>
<P>
Gorbachev stopped short of advocating any specific proposals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
